      <h2 id="rate-structure">The rate is not the price</h2>
      <p>Every pricing page shows you a rate. None of them show you the structure — and the structure is where the money goes. An hourly bookkeeper at $40 who takes eleven hours costs more than one at $60 who takes six, and you won't know which you have until <a href="#">the close runs long</a>.</p>
      <p>The same is true of "starting at $300/mo" subscriptions. The starting price is real; so is the repricing call after onboarding, when the provider has your data and switching feels expensive.</p>
      <blockquote class="pull-quote" style="margin:var(--space-10) 0">
        <p>Hourly billing rewards slow work. Subscriptions reward repricing. A written fixed fee is the only structure where the incentive points your way.</p>
      </blockquote>
      <h2 id="market-rates">What the market actually charges</h2>
      <p>Across the files we audit, transactional bookkeeping runs $25–$50/hr; full-charge work with a real month-end close runs $50–$85/hr. As a monthly service, clean low-volume books cost $300–$800; payroll, inventory, or multiple entities push engagements to $800–$2,500. Cleanup is its own market — see <a href="#">our cleanup pricing tiers</a> for what severity actually costs.</p>
      <h2 id="three-questions">The three questions that price a provider</h2>
      <p>Ask for the price in writing before work begins. Ask who works your file. Ask what cadence the books are reconciled on. The answers predict your experience better than the rate does. If you want our answers to those questions, <a href="#">the file review is free</a>.</p>
      <p class="meta-reviewed" style="margin-top:var(--space-8)"><span>Published: 2026-03-14</span><span>Updated: 2026-06-02</span><span>Reviewed: 2026-06-10 · Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor</span></p>
    </article>
